We ordered two 9-inch gluten free pizzas on Uber eats. The total came out to $60 for just two small pizzas. But we were still excited to get our pizzas and try their gluten free option. The crust on the pizzas was terrible. It was thick, dense and soggy. There was no crispness to it at all. We have tried many small pizza business that make a thin, crispy gluten free crust so we thought we couldn’t go wrong. Additionally, they offer prosciutto as a topping but it wasn’t actually prosciutto. More like a very thick soft bacon on top. Prosciutto is supposed to be super thin sliced. This was so disappointing especially since it was so expensive!

Delicious wood-fired pizza! The Margherita pizza isn't Neapolitan as the crust and dough are a bit thicker. The pizza is a bit dry and my hubby didn't enjoy his as much as il Canale or 90 second pizza.  While simpler is usually better, I prefer a pizza loaded up with toppings here as Paradiso has super fresh ingredients and knows how to slice and dice veggies! Ironically, I had a veggie pizza at Domino's the night before, and could definitely taste the difference in freshness of the ingredients and craftmanship of the pizza, Paradiso was hands-down the winner!  My custom pesto pizza packed with veggies was bursting with flavor in every bite from the creamy fresh goat cheese. There was no shortage of cheese and It's sourced from a farm in PA. The diced roasted eggplant, roasted garlic, spinach, and thinly sliced red onions were delicious and elevated the flavor. The mozzarella cheese had a nice subtle flavor but a bit overpowered by the goat cheese. Of the half dozen or so toppings, the only one I would skip was the chopped chunky sweet red peppers, the raw peppers didn't pair well with the pesto sauce and other ingredients. Raw peppers would pair better with tomato sauce or roasted peppers would be tasty! I would love to try the toppings with a twist on a tomato sauce pie and swap out the goat cheese for the buffalo cheese - next time!  The Pomme Mary cider is on the drier side with a crisp taste and a hint of sweetness. Perfect balance between sweet and dry.  The tables in front of the restaurant are 6 feet apart and have a nice umbrella awning, perfect for shielding us from the rain.  Pizza Paradiso is a staple of DC and visited 1/2 dozen times over the years at the other locations in Dupont and Alexandria. The Georgetown location is my favorite! Can't wait to be back!

I came to Pizzeria Paradiso on a busy Friday night and was pleasantly surprised that I was seated quickly. The service here is decent-- I do wish the waiting staff was a bit more attentive and that they made you feel more welcome. Overall, this restaurant is just "okay". It's not bad, it's not great.  The atmosphere is fine but it's nothing worth writing home about. You come here for pizza and that's where Paradiso let me down. The crust is decent but the sauces, cheeses, and toppings are all just "okay". Mostly bland or obscured, the toppings add little to no flavor to each pizza.  Things I Liked: Bruschetta - The bread was crisp while the tomatoes and herbs tasted fresh.  Things I Disliked: Margherita Pizza - The cheese and basil simply failed to add any substantial flavor to the pizza. It was a very forgettable dish-- something I would not expect given the price I'm paying.  Ultimately, this restaurant is merely average. Neither the food, the service, nor the atmosphere are stand-out enough to make you overlook one another. It seems as though the only reason it does well is because of its prime location in Georgetown.
